{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622603"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:05:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:05:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16808"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16808"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.62,0.07,0.05,0.21,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9499"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67916"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9499"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16808"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53382"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4938"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5207"},{"type":"tags","id":"5208"},{"type":"tags","id":"8512"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"},{"type":"tags","id":"10315"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22432"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22453"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67916"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENon-depolarising neuromuscular blocking drugs are commonly used during general anaesthesia to facilitate endotracheal intubation and provide muscle relaxation during surgery.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of non-depolarising neuromuscular blockers?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Competitive antagonism at nicotinic acetylcholine receptors","Blockade of voltage-gated sodium channels","Depolarisation of the motor end plate","Inhibition of acetylcholine release","Prevention of acetylcholine synthesis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENon-depolarising neuromuscular blockers work through \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompetitive antagonism at nicotinic acetylcholine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E at the neuromuscular junction. They bind reversibly to these receptors without activating them, preventing acetylcholine from binding and initiating muscle contraction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlockade of voltage-gated sodium channels\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; these drugs act specifically at acetylcholine receptors and do not affect ion channels directly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDepolarisation of the motor end plate\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of depolarising neuromuscular blockers such as suxamethonium, which causes initial muscle fasciculations due to its depolarising effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of acetylcholine release\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect, as these drugs act post-synaptically at the receptor level rather than affecting neurotransmitter release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-depolarising neuromuscular blockers do not interfere with the production or storage of acetylcholine, so cannot \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevent acetylcholine synthesis.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe competitive nature of these drugs means their effects can be reversed by increasing acetylcholine concentration at the neuromuscular junction, which is the basis for using acetylcholinesterase inhibitors as reversal agents.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-depolarising neuromuscular blockers competitively bind to nicotinic acetylcholine receptors at the neuromuscular junction to prevent muscle contraction.","Non-depolarising neuromuscular blockers do not cause muscle depolarisation or fasciculations.","Common examples include rocuronium, vecuronium, and pancuronium."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53382"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16808"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53382"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T20:43:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T20:44:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9499"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67916"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group"